<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
  <chapter xml:id="ch-oo-intro" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Object-Oriented Programming: Introduction</title>

    <p>
      In the following five chapters you'll learn about
      <em>object-oriented programming</em> (OOP). OOP is a little more
      challenging in R than in other languages because:
    </p>

    <p><ul>
      <li><p>
        There are multiple OOP systems to choose from. In this book, I'll
        focus on the three that I believe are most important: S3, R6, and S4.
        S3 and S4 are provided by base R. R6 is provided by the R6 package,
        and is similar to the Reference Classes, or R5, that are also provided
        by base R.
      </p></li>
      <li><p>
        There is disagreement about the relative importance of the OOP systems.
        I think S3 and R6 are most important, followed by S4. Base R mostly
        uses S3 and S4.
      </p></li>
      <li><p>
        S3 and S4 use generic function OOP which is rather different from the
        encapsulated OOP used by most languages popular today.
      </p></li>
    </ul></p>

    <p>
      The OOP chapters are organised as follows:
    </p>

    <p><ol>
      <li><p>
        <xref ref="ch-base-types"/> gives you the necessary foundation by
        describing the differences between base and OO objects.
      </p></li>
      <li><p>
        <xref ref="ch-s3"/> introduces S3, the simplest and most commonly
        used OOP system.
      </p></li>
      <li><p>
        <xref ref="ch-r6"/> introduces R6, an encapsulated OOP system built
        on top of environments.
      </p></li>
      <li><p>
        <xref ref="ch-s4"/> introduces S4, a rigorous, formal OOP system.
      </p></li>
      <li><p>
        <xref ref="ch-oo-tradeoffs"/> compares these three main OOP systems.
      </p></li>
    </ol></p>

  </chapter>
